messages.subject: Re: [AlwaysLearning] Re: Poop and Pee
messages.msgSnippet: In a message dated 12/28/01 1:42:43 AM, moonmeghan@yahoo.com writes:
messages.messageBody:
In a message dated 12/28/01 1:42:43 AM, moonmeghan@... writes:

<< That reminds me of a book we have called The Story of
the Little Mole Who Went in Search of Whodunit by
Wener Holzwarth and Wolf Erlbruch. It's a laugh! >>

I was surprized it was by Germans, for sure.

We have it too, and it is sweet, educational, and totally about poop
(although there is a revenge sub-plop... <hee hee>)

I bought it when I went to look for Everyone Poops (or whatever it is) and
they were out, but the bookseller directed me to this much-better book.

I had a book on the history of toilets, and before I had even finished
reading it, I loaned it to a hospitalized friend. His wife ended up giving
it to Goodwill with some other books. I was grumpy--I've never seen another
copy of it. I think it was British, too...

Sandra

messages.subject: Re: Poop and Pee
messages.messageBody:
<<<<It reminds me of a story my Mom read my boys
called "Harris and me" by Gary Paulsen....she has no
hang ups about poop and pee jokes. In fact she's
usually the first to introduce weird, scary, funny and
rude information to my kids, which they love.In the
book, one of the boys pees on the electric
fence....you can imagine the humor in THAT!
Ren>>>>

That reminds me of a book we have called The Story of
the Little Mole Who Went in Search of Whodunit by
Wener Holzwarth and Wolf Erlbruch. It's a laugh!

Meghan :-)
